'''Giovanni Alejandro Reyna''' (born November 13, 2002) is an American professional [[Association football|soccer]] player<!--Do not change to "football". Wikipedia articles are written in the style of English most associated with the subject, and as Reyna is American, please use American English --> who plays for [[Bundesliga]] club [[Borussia Mönchengladbach]] and the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]].

Reyna began his youth career with his hometown club, [[New York City FC]], and had his breakthrough with Bundesliga club [[Borussia Dortmund]]. During the [[2019–20 DFB-Pokal]] he became the youngest scorer in the German Cup's history at the age of 17, and was a part of the team that won the following [[2020–21 DFB-Pokal]].<ref name="CBS" /> In 2020 he became the youngest Bundesliga player to create a hat trick of assists.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Gio Reyna makes history with assist hat-trick for Borussia Dortmund |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/gio-reyna-makes-history-assist-hat-trick-for-borussia-dortmund-usa-usmnt-13112 |access-date=2023-06-06 |website=bundesliga.com - the official Bundesliga website |language=en}}</ref> He was on the final shortlist of the [[2021 Ballon d'Or|2021 Kopa Trophy]].<ref name=":3">{{Cite web |date=2021-11-23 |title=Pedri wins prestigious Golden Boy award for 2021 |url=https://www.nbcsports.com/soccer/news/golden-boy-award-2021-pedri-full-list-rankings |access-date=2023-10-15 |website=NBC Sports |language=en-US}}</ref> He moved to Borussia Mönchengladbach in August 2025.

Born to U.S. national team players [[Claudio Reyna]] and [[Danielle Reyna]], he has represented the United States at several youth levels, scoring 16 goals in 31 youth caps. Reyna made his debut for the senior team in November 2020 and won the [[CONCACAF Nations League]] in [[2021 CONCACAF Nations League Finals|2021]], [[2023 CONCACAF Nations League Finals|2023]], and [[2024 CONCACAF Nations League Finals|2024]], winning the best player overall of the latter.<ref name=":1" /> Individually he won a [[U.S. Soccer Player of the Year|U.S. Soccer Young Male Player of the Year]] award in 2020.

==Early life==
Reyna was born in [[Sunderland|Sunderland, England]], to American parents, [[Claudio Reyna]] and [[Danielle Reyna]], when his father was playing for [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]. Both of his parents are former soccer players, who played for the United States [[United States men's national soccer team|men's]] and [[United States women's national soccer team|women's]] national teams, respectively. His family moved back to the United States, settling in [[Bedford (town), New York|Bedford, New York]], in 2007 when Reyna was five years old.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://jr10corp.com/pages/about-jr10-corp |title=ABOUT JR10 CORP - Jr10clothing |access-date=August 17, 2021 |archive-date=September 18, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210918131841/https://jr10corp.com/pages/about-jr10-corp |url-status=dead }}</ref> He joined the academy team of his hometown club, [[New York City FC|New York City]], in 2015 and kept playing with the City academy teams until 2019, when he moved to [[Germany]] to join [[Borussia Dortmund]]'s academy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dortmund sign U.S. youth Gio Reyna from NYCFC |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/soccer-transfers/story/3890386/dortmund-sign-us-youth-gio-reyna-from-nycfc |website=ESPN FC |access-date=May 25, 2020 |date=July 1, 2019}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Borussia Dortmund===
====2019–20 season: Breakthrough====
On January 18, 2020, Reyna made his [[Bundesliga]] debut for [[Borussia Dortmund]], coming on as a substitute in the 72nd minute, in a 5–3 win against [[FC Augsburg]].<ref name="mlssoccer">{{cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2020/01/18/new-york-city-fc-academy-alum-giovanni-reyna-makes-bundesliga-debut-borussia|title=New York City FC academy alum Giovanni Reyna makes Bundesliga debut in Borussia Dortmund win|website=mlssoccer.com|date=January 18, 2020}}</ref> Hence, he became the youngest American, aged 17 years and 66 days, ever to appear in the Bundesliga, breaking a record previously set by [[Christian Pulisic]].<ref name="mlssoccer" />

On February 4, Reyna scored his first professional goal in a 3–2 defeat to [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]] in the [[2019–20 DFB-Pokal|DFB-Pokal]] Round of 16.<ref name="CBS" /> In doing so, he became the youngest goalscorer in [[DFB-Pokal|German Cup]] history.<ref name="CBS">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/news/gio-reyna-rising-u-s-soccer-star-scores-gorgeous-strike-for-first-professional-goal-with-dortmund/|title=Gio Reyna, rising U.S. soccer star, scores gorgeous strike for first professional goal with Dortmund|website=CBS Sports|date=February 4, 2020|access-date=February 5, 2020}}</ref> On February 18, 2020, Reyna became the third-youngest player ever to appear in a knockout game of the [[UEFA Champions League]] when he came on as a substitute in the 67th minute against [[Paris Saint-Germain]]. Nine minutes later, Reyna set up [[Erling Haaland]]'s game-winning goal for Borussia Dortmund in the first leg of the Round of 16, becoming the youngest American to play and record an assist in a Champions League fixture.<ref>{{Cite web|title=USA teenager Gio Reyna overtakes Christian Pulisic in Borussia Dortmund and UEFA Champions League history books|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/gio-reyna-makes-champions-league-history-with-debut-assist-overtakes-pulisic-dortmund-psg-10029|access-date=May 15, 2021|website=bundesliga.com - the official Bundesliga website|language=en}}</ref>

On May 16, Reyna was set to start his first Bundesliga match for Borussia Dortmund in their derby against [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]], but suffered a calf injury during warm-ups.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hamilton |first1=Tom |title=Dortmund, USMNT prospect Giovanni Reyna injured when set for first start |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/borussia-dortmund/story/4095121/dortmundusmnt-prospect-giovanni-reyna-injured-when-set-for-first-start |website=ESPN |access-date=May 16, 2020 |date=May 16, 2020}}</ref> Reyna returned on May 23 and played in the final 11 minutes of a 2–0 victory at [[VfL Wolfsburg]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Uersfeld |first1=Stephan |date=May 22, 2020 |title=USMNT hopeful Gio Reyna back for Dortmund, Favre admits Bundesliga return a 'danger' |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/borussia-dortmund/story/4098146/usmnt-hopeful-gio-reyna-back-for-dortmundfavre-admits-return-a-danger |access-date=May 24, 2020 |website=ESPN FC}}</ref>

==== 2020–21 season: DFB-Pokal win ====

On September 14, 2020, Reyna started in a [[DFB-Pokal]] match and scored with a free kick in a 5–0 win against [[MSV Duisburg]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Meyers |first=Brian |date=September 14, 2020 |title=BVB Post Match Report: BVB dismantle Duisburg 5-0 |url=https://www.fearthewall.com/2020/9/14/21436817/bvb-post-match-report-bvb-dismantle-duisburg-5-0 |access-date=September 17, 2020 |website=Fear The Wall |language=en}}</ref> On September 19, 2020, Reyna scored his first Bundesliga goal in a 3–0 win against [[Borussia Mönchengladbach]], aged 17 years and 311 days,<ref>{{cite news |date=September 19, 2020 |title=Giovanni Reyna becomes second-youngest American to score in Bundesliga |newspaper=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2020/09/19/giovanni-reyna-second-youngest-american-bundesliga/}}</ref> to become the second youngest American scorer in Bundesliga history behind [[Christian Pulisic]], who was aged 17 years and 211 days.<ref>{{cite web |date=September 19, 2020 |title=WATCH: Gio Reyna scores first career Bundesliga goal |url=https://www.starsandstripesfc.com/2020/9/19/21446787/watch-gio-reyna-scores-first-career-bundesliga-goal |website=Stars and Stripes FC}}</ref>[[File:Borussia Dortmund vs FC Zenit 10-28-2020 (1).jpg|thumb|Reyna playing for Dortmund in 2020.]]On October 3, 2020, in his third league appearance of the 2020–21 season, Reyna assisted 3 goals—a brace to [[Erling Haaland]] and an [[Emre Can]] header from a corner kick, to beat [[SC Freiburg]] 4–0.<ref>{{Cite web|agency=Associated Press|date=October 3, 2020|title=Reyna stars for Dortmund in 4-0 win against Freiburg|url=https://www.dailyherald.com/article/20201003/sports/310039953|access-date=October 3, 2020|website=Daily Herald|language=en-US}}</ref> As a result, Reyna became the first American to record a [[Hat trick|hat trick of assists]] in one of the 5 major European leagues since [[Steve Cherundolo]] did it for [[Hannover 96|Hannover]] in March 2008, and the youngest player to ever do so in the Bundesliga.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Dortmund teenager Reyna makes history with three-assist display against Freiburg {{!}} Goal.com|url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/dortmund-teenager-reyna-makes-history-with-three-assist/182voq5murdp71tazuc6q084zr|access-date=May 15, 2021|website=www.goal.com}}</ref>

On December 5, Reyna scored his second [[Bundesliga]] goal against [[Eintracht Frankfurt]], with a near post finish just inside the 18-yard box. This goal made him the second youngest American to score twice in the league after [[Christian Pulisic]] did so for the same club as Reyna, [[Borussia Dortmund]].<ref>{{Cite magazine|last=Jackson|first=Wilton|title=USMNT's Reyna Scores Stunner for Dortmund|url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2020/12/05/gio-reyna-scores-second-bundesliga-goal-dortmund-video|access-date=December 5, 2020|magazine=Sports Illustrated|date=December 5, 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref> On December 22, he was voted the U.S. Soccer's Young Male Player of the Year for 2020.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|date=December 22, 2020|title=Dortmund's Gio Reyna named U.S. Soccer's Young Male Player of the Year|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/united-states-usa/story/4271615/dortmunds-gio-reyna-named-us-soccers-young-male-player-of-the-year|access-date=December 22, 2020|website=ESPN}}</ref>

Reyna was a second-half substitute for Dortmund in their 4–1 victory over [[RB Leipzig]] in the [[2021 DFB-Pokal Final]] on May 13, 2021. His involvement in the match marks him as the youngest American to appear in a domestic cup final in Europe, a record previously held by his international teammate Christian Pulisic.<ref name=DFBW>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/article/bundesliga-borussia-dortmund-dortmund-europe-leipzig-57d576ad46190c226251b8f92669dbf8|title=Borussia Dortmund beats Leipzig 4-1 in German Cup final|website=AP|date=May 13, 2021}}</ref> For his strong youth performances, he was on the final shortlist for the 2021 [[Golden Boy (award)|Golden Boy]]; finishing 6th, and [[2021 Ballon d'Or|2021 Kopa Trophy]]; finishing 9th.<ref name=":3" />

====2021–2023: Super-sub and injuries====
On July 28, 2021, Dortmund announced that Reyna would wear the number 7 shirt for the upcoming season, previously worn by [[Jadon Sancho]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/borussia-dortmund/story/4440598/usmnts-giovanni-reyna-takes-jadon-sanchos-no-7-shirt-at-borussia-dortmund|title=USMNT's Giovanni Reyna takes Jadon Sancho's No. 7 shirt at Borussia Dortmund|website=ESPN|date=July 28, 2021}}</ref> On August 27, he became the youngest player to make 50 [[Bundesliga]] appearances during the league match against [[Hoffenheim (football club)|Hoffenheim]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Gio Reyna makes history as Borussia Dortmund beat Hoffenheim in dramatic thriller|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/borussia-dortmund-hoffenheim-live-line-ups-stats-haaland-reyna-malen-reus-17042|access-date=August 28, 2021|website=bundesliga.com - the official Bundesliga website|language=en}}</ref> Reyna suffered a series of injuries that caused him to miss the majority of the [[2021–22 Borussia Dortmund season|2021–22 season]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Creditor |first=Avi |title=USMNT's Reyna Exits in Tears After Suffering Another Injury for Dortmund |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2022/04/08/gio-reyna-injury-borussia-dortmund-stuttgart-usmnt-video |access-date=September 10, 2022 |magazine=Sports Illustrated |date=April 8, 2022 |language=en-us}}</ref>

On September 6, 2022, Reyna became the first American player to provide two assists in a Champions League match in a 3–0 win against [[F.C. Copenhagen|Copenhagen]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Supersub Gio Reyna Comes On And Becomes First American With 2 Assists In UCL Game |website=The18 |url=https://the18.com/en/soccer-news/gio-reyna-assists-vs-copenhagen-set-america-record-in-ucl |access-date=September 10, 2022}}</ref> Returning from injuries, on October 22, he scored his first Bundesliga goal in 421 days, adding to a 5–0 victory against [[VfB Stuttgart]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Koons |first=Zach |date=2022-10-22 |title=Watch: 19-Year-Old American Soccer Star Scores First Goal in Over 400 Days After Run of Injuries |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2022/10/22/gio-reyna-scores-first-goal-over-400-days-borussia-dortmund-stuttgart-usmnt-video |access-date=2023-05-28 |magazine=Sports Illustrated}}</ref> Returning from the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]], on January 22, 2023, he scored a game-winning goal off the bench against [[FC Augsburg]] in the 78th minute, winning 4–3.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-01-22 |title=Borussia Dortmund 4-3 Augsburg: Gio Reyna fires winner in Bundesliga thriller |url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/bundesliga/2022-2023/borussia-dortmund-v-fc-augsburg-bundesliga-live_sto9338717/story.shtml |access-date=2023-05-23 |website=Eurosport}}</ref> Three days later, he scored another game-winning goal off the bench in stoppage time in the 93rd minute against [[Mainz 05]], winning 2–1.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-01-25 |title=WATCH: USMNT star Gio Reyna scores stoppage time winner for Dortmund vs Mainz |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/usmnt-gio-reyna-scores-stoppage-time-winner-dortmund-vs-mainz/blt5610e7324c419ee3 |access-date=2023-05-23 |website=www.goal.com}}</ref>

Coming into his final season match against Mainz, Reyna had the second best minute-per-goal ratio of a [[Big Five (association football)|top five European league]] player for the 2022–23 season after [[Erling Haaland]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=20-year-old Gio Reyna assisted both of BVB's goals today while only being subbed on in the 63rd minute! |url=https://twitter.com/FOXSoccer/status/1662502581749559296?s=20 |access-date=2023-05-28 |website=FOX Sports Twitter}}</ref> On May 27, during the final game of the [[2022–23 Bundesliga]] where Dortmund was in first place, Reyna came off the bench in the 63rd minute when Dortmund were 2–0 down against [[Mainz 05]] and created two assists to level the game 2–2. The game ended in a draw and Dortmund was the league runner-up to Bayern.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-05-27 |title=Dortmund throw away chance at Bundesliga title as USMNT's Gio Reyna is unable to save the day against Bayern |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/dortmund-mainz-bundesliga-reyna-usmnt/blt454acff9ac212851 |access-date=2023-05-27 |website=www.goal.com}}</ref> Reyna finished the season with four assists and his highest Bundesliga goal amount with seven goals, five of which were as a substitute.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Giovanni Reyna Stats - Goals, xG, Assists & xA  |url=https://footystats.org/players/usa/giovanni-reyna |access-date=2023-05-28 |website=footystats.org }}</ref>

==== 2024–2025: Loan and playtime decline ====
On January 31, 2024, Reyna extended his contract with Borussia Dortmund until June 30, 2026, and was subsequently loaned to [[Premier League]] club [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] until the end of the [[2023–24 Nottingham Forest F.C. season|2023–24 season]].<ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |date=31 January 2024 |title=Reyna verlängert und wechselt bis Saisonende nach England |trans-title=Reyna extends and moves to England until the end of the season |url=http://www.bvb.de/ger/News/Uebersicht/Reyna-verlaengert-und-wechselt-bis-Saisonende-nach-England/ |access-date=31 January 2024 |publisher=Borussia Dortmund |language=de}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |date=31 January 2024 |title=Forest complete Gio Reyna signing |url=https://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/2024/january/31/forest-complete-gio-reyna-signing/ |access-date=31 January 2024 |website= |publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C.}}</ref>

He made his debut for Forest as a 78th-minute substitute for [[Anthony Elanga]] in a 1–1 draw against [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] in the [[2023–24 Premier League|Premier League]] on February 4.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68120825|title=AFC Bournemouth 1-1 Nottm Forest|website=BBC Sport|date=4 February 2024|access-date=4 February 2024}}</ref> On April 13, Reyna recorded an assist against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] in his first start of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-04-13 |title=Gio Reyna makes huge statement as USMNT star provides big assist against Wolves in first Nottingham Forest start |url=https://www.goal.com/en-in/lists/gio-reyna-usmnt-nottingham-forest-wolves-assist/bltade0ad9d9fa59a73 |access-date=2024-04-14 |website=www.goal.com}}</ref> He ultimately only featured in 10 matches for Forest and returned to Dortmund, finishing the 2023–24 season with no goals for both clubs.

Reyna played only sporadically throughout the [[2024–25 Borussia Dortmund season|2024–25 season]], playing only 341 league minutes and scoring two goals with one assist.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-05-21 |title=Career crossroads: As Dortmund's Gio Reyna seeks an express lane out of limbo, it's possible a soccer-free summer is exactly what 22-year-old USMNT midfielder needs {{!}} Goal.com US |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/lists/as-dortmund-s-gio-reyna-looks-for-an-express-lane-out-of-career-limbo-it-s-possible-soccer-free-summer-is-exactly-what-22-year-old-usmnt-midfielder-needs/blta63b6acdf1d63da3 |access-date=2025-05-22 |website=www.goal.com |language=en-US}}</ref>

=== Borussia Mönchengladbach ===
On August 23, 2025, Reyna made a permanent move to [[Borussia Mönchengladbach]] until 2028 for around €7 million.<ref>{{Cite web |last=read |first=Bulinews·1 min |date=2025-08-23 |title=Official: Gio Reyna joins Borussia Mönchengladbach |url=https://ca.sports.yahoo.com/news/official-gio-reyna-joins-borussia-155800206.html |access-date=2025-08-23 |website=Yahoo Sports |language=en-US}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club in the stoppage time of a 3–1 away defeat against FC Augsburg on 9 May 2026.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/747009/borussia-monchengladbach-fc-augsburg |title=FC Augsburg 3–1 Borussia Mönchengladbach |publisher=ESPN |date=9 May 2026 }}</ref> However, his debut season at the club was hampered by recurring injuries and inconsistent minutes, as he managed only four league starts and one goal across all competitions.<ref>{{cite web |last=Carlisle |first=Jeff |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/48911140/usa-gio-reyna-mature-controversy-world-cup-2022-2026 |title='Matured' Gio Reyna tired of discussing World Cup controversy |publisher=ESPN |date=29 May 2026 }}</ref>

==International career==
[[File:Gio Reyna USMNT v Belgium Mar 28 2026-194.jpg|thumb|upright|Reyna in 2026]]
After representing the United States at several youth levels, Reyna received his first call up to the senior [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] squad for matches against [[Wales national football team|Wales]] and [[Panama national football team|Panama]] in November 2020.<ref name=":1">{{cite web|url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2020/11/usmnt-roster-announcement-berhalter-24-players-november-camp-friendlies-wales-panama |title=USMNT ROSTER ANNOUNCEMENT: BERHALTER CALLS 24 PLAYERS FOR NOVEMBER CAMP MATCHES VS WALES AND PANAMA |date=November 3, 2020 |publisher=ussoccer.com |access-date=November 3, 2020}}</ref> On November 12, 2020, a day before his 18th birthday, Reyna made his senior national team debut against Wales.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2020/11/usmnt-0-wales-0-match-report-stats|title=USA 0 - Wales 0: Match Report & Stats}}</ref> In the following game, a 6–2 friendly victory over Panama, Reyna started and scored his first senior goal directly from a free kick.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2020/11/usmnt-6-panama-2-match-report-stats|title = USA 6 - Panama 2: Match Report & Stats}}</ref>

In 2021, Reyna won the inaugural [[2019–20 CONCACAF Nations League|CONCACAF Nations League]] and scored in the 3–2 victory against [[Mexico–United States soccer rivalry|rivals]] [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] in [[2021 CONCACAF Nations League final|the final]].<ref name=":2" />

On March 24, 2022, during a third-round [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – CONCACAF third round#Matchday 12|2022 World Cup qualification match]] against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] at [[Estadio Azteca]], Reyna dribbled past six Mexican defenders in a single run before being dispossessed; after the match it was compared to [[Diego Maradona]]'s "Goal of the Century" run during the quarter-finals of the [[Argentina v England (1986 FIFA World Cup)|1986 World Cup]], which was also at the Azteca.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Creditor |first=Avi |title=USMNT's Reyna Dazzles With Slaloming Dribble vs. Mexico |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2022/03/25/gio-reyna-dribble-usmnt-mexico-video-world-cup-qualifying |access-date=September 10, 2022 |magazine=Sports Illustrated |date=March 25, 2022 |language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=mlssoccer |title=USMNT's Gio Reyna draws Maradona comparison after solo run vs. Mexico {{!}} MLSSoccer.com |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/usmnt-s-gio-reyna-draws-maradona-comparison-after-solo-run-vs-mexico |access-date=September 10, 2022 |website=mlssoccer |language=en}}</ref>

In the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]], Reyna played only 52 minutes in four games. His sidelining throughout the group stage of the tournament led to speculation from analysts of possible issues within the team.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Stejskal |first=Paul Tenorio and Sam |title=Gio Reyna minutes limited |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3991695/2022/12/11/gio-reyna-usmnt-gregg-berhalter/ |access-date=2022-12-12 |website=The Athletic |language=en}}</ref> USMNT head coach [[Gregg Berhalter]] publicly addressed issues regarding an anonymous player for a lack of commitment and poor attitude, and confirmed that the team had held a meeting to determine if that player were to remain with the team in Qatar for the remainder of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://worldsoccertalk.com/news/gregg-berhalter-airs-out-dirty-laundry-on-gio-reyna-20221212-WST-412086.html|title=Gregg Berhalter airs dirty laundry on Gio Reyna|author=Kyle Fansler|website=worldsoccertalk.com|date=December 12, 2022|accessdate=January 4, 2023}}</ref> On December 12, 2022, Reyna confirmed that he was the aforementioned player about whom Berhalter was speaking, and apologized for his behavior while criticizing the decision to publicize the information.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Gio Reyna criticizes Gregg Berhalter in Instagram post |url=https://worldsoccertalk.com/news/gio-reyna-criticizes-gregg-berhalter-in-instagram-post-20221212-WST-412150.html |access-date=2023-01-04 |website=World Soccer Talk |date=December 12, 2022 |language=en}}</ref> In January 2023, it was revealed that Berhalter had been confronted during the tournament about damaging personal information that was floated to superiors. [[Danielle Reyna]], Reyna's mother, confirmed that she was the one who informed the [[United States Soccer Federation|U.S. Soccer Federation]] about the episode of violent behavior between Berhalter and his wife from 1991.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-01-04 |title=Gio Reyna's mother gave USSF Berhalter info |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/united-states-usa/story/4844539/reynas-told-us-soccer-about-past-gregg-berhalter-domestic-violence-incident-sources |access-date=2023-01-04 |website=ESPN.com |language=en}}</ref> Ultimately this led to an investigation of Berhalter that found the incident to be isolated and no reason to not employ him as a coach.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Tenorio |first=Paul |date=2024-03-26 |title=U.S. Soccer Gregg Berhalter investigation: What was found, Reynas' involvement and what's next |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4304622/2023/03/13/gregg-berhalter-us-soccer-investigation-explained/ |access-date=2025-11-24 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

During the [[2023 CONCACAF Nations League Finals|2023 CONCACAF Nations League]], Reyna recorded two assists in the United States' 2–0 victory over [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]] in the [[2023 CONCACAF Nations League final|final]], where he was named man of the match.<ref>{{Cite web |last=mlssoccer |title=USMNT Player Ratings: Gio Reyna dismantles Canada in Nations League final {{!}} MLSSoccer.com |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/usmnt-player-ratings-gio-reyna-dismantles-canada-in-nations-league-final |access-date=2023-06-19 |website=mlssoccer |language=en}}</ref> On October 17, 2023, he recorded his first international brace in a 4–0 friendly win over [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=2023-10-18 |title=Gio Reyna scores twice as the USMNT rolls to a rout of Ghana |language=en-US |newspaper=Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2023/10/17/usmnt-ghana-gio-reyna/ |access-date=2023-10-19 |issn=0190-8286}}</ref> During the [[2024 CONCACAF Nations League Finals]], Reyna assisted two goals in the United States' 3–1 semi-final victory over [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-03-22 |title='Gio Reyna's quality is unquestionable' - Gregg Berhalter fires back at critics after Nottingham Forest midfielder's two-assist masterclass against Jamaica in CONCACAF Nations League win {{!}} Goal.com US |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/lists/gio-reyna-usmnt-gregg-berhalter-jamaica-concacaf-nations-league/blt14ed9b92b26a85cf |access-date=2024-03-25 |website=www.goal.com |language=en-US}}</ref> In the following game, he scored in the 2–0 [[2024 CONCACAF Nations League final|final]] victory against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], again being named man of the match as well as the best player of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.starsandstripesfc.com/2024/3/28/24114240/usa-usmnt-mexico-2024-concacaf-nations-league-finals-man-of-the-match-reyna-pulisic-adams |title=USA vs. Mexico, 2024 Concacaf Nations League Final: Man of the Match |publisher=Stars and Stripes FC |date=28 March 2024 }}</ref>

On 26 May 2026, Reyna was named in the 26-man squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]] hosted on home soil.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2026/05/usmnt/us-mens-national-team-head-coach-mauricio-pochettino-names-26-player-roster-for-fifa-world-cup-2026 |title=U.S. Men's National Team Head Coach Mauricio Pochettino Names 26-Player Roster for FIFA World Cup 2026 |publisher=[[United States Soccer Federation]] |date=May 26, 2026 |access-date=May 26, 2026}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Giovanni is the son of former professional soccer player and [[United States men's national soccer team|United States men's national team]] player [[Claudio Reyna]],<ref name="US Soccer">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ussoccer.com/players/r/giovanni-reyna|title=Giovanni Reyna {{!}} U.S. Soccer Official Website|website=ussoccer.com|language=en|access-date=October 27, 2019}}</ref> and [[Danielle Reyna]], a former member of the [[United States women's national soccer team]].<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/gio-reyna-who-is-borussia-dortmund-s-latest-american-sensation-new-york-city-fc-3914 |title= Gio Reyna: Who is Borussia Dortmund's latest American sensation? |access-date=January 18, 2020 |website=bundesliga.com}}</ref> Reyna is of Argentine-Portuguese descent through his father's parents and of [[Irish Americans|Irish-American]] descent through his mother.<ref name="Wahl 2018">{{cite magazine | last=Wahl | first=Grant | title=The Reyna Family's Story of Loss and Legacy | magazine=Sports Illustrated | date=December 12, 2018 | url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2018/12/12/claudio-reyna-family-jack-death-giovanni-dortmund | access-date=April 7, 2021}}</ref> His older brother, Jack, died of brain cancer in 2012, at the age of 13.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The Reyna Family's Story of Loss and Legacy|url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2018/12/12/claudio-reyna-family-jack-death-giovanni-dortmund |access-date=November 29, 2022 |magazine=Sports Illustrated |date=December 12, 2018|first=Grant|last=Wahl}}</ref>

Reyna started his international career by playing with the United States' youth teams, but after impressing with Borussia Dortmund, he attracted interest from the [[Portugal national football team|Portuguese]], [[England national football team|English]] and [[Argentina national football team|Argentine]] national teams.<ref>{{Cite web|title='The U.S. is my home' - Reyna shuts down reports of England call-up {{!}} Goal.com|url=https://www.goal.com/en-ph/news/the-us-is-my-home-reyna-shuts-down-reports-of-england-call/nmxe1kebyysf1169c3gxzuoug|access-date=March 26, 2021|website=www.goal.com}}</ref> Ultimately, in a March 2020 interview with ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', Reyna declared his intent to play for the United States: "I'm aware of the rumors, but it's quite clear for me. I only want to play for the United States. That's my home country."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2020/03/05/gio-reyna-usa-international-choice-borussia-dortmund |title=Gio Reyna Ends Faux Suspense Over His International 'Choice', Will Play for USA |website=si.com |date=March 5, 2020 }}</ref>

He was named after his father's former [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] teammate [[Giovanni van Bronckhorst]].<ref name="US Soccer"/> His high level of play has earned him the nickname "The American Dream" by former teammate [[Erling Haaland]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=June 21, 2020 |title=Erling Haaland Reveals Nickname for Wonderkid Teammate Gio Reyna |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/erling-haaland-nickname-wonderkid-gio-reyna |access-date=September 10, 2022 |website=90min.com |language=en-GB}}</ref> Reyna is close friends with United States teammate [[Joe Scally]]; both players began attending the New York City FC youth academy in 2015.<ref>{{Citation |title=Tim Ream INTERVIEWS Gio Reyna & Joe Scally 😂 {{!}} The American Dream | date=October 14, 2023 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=shIxbglFYc0 |access-date=2023-11-13 |language=en}}</ref>

